{{Infobox glacier | child = | name = Blades Glacier | other_name = | photo = King Edward VII Land map.png | photo_alt = | photo_caption = Location of King Edward VII Land (marked in orange) within the Ross Dependency | map = Antarctica | map_width = | map_alt = | map_caption = Location of Blades Glacier in [[Antarctica]] | mark = Blue_pog.svg | type = | location = [[King Edward VII Land]] | coordinates = {{coord|77|38|S|153|00|W|region:AQ|format=dms|display=inline}} | coords_ref = | area = | length = | width = | thickness = unknown | elevation_max = | elevation_min = | terminus = [[Dalton Glacier]] | status = unknown | embedded = }}
'''Blades Glacier''' ({{Coord|77|38|S|153|0|W|source:GNIS|display=inline,title}}) is a [[glacier]] flowing east from the snow-covered saddle just north of [[La Gorce Peak]], [[Alexandra Mountains]]. It merges with [[Dalton Glacier]] on the north side of [[Edward VII Peninsula]]. It was mapped by the [[United States Geological Survey]] from surveys and from [[U.S. Navy]] air photos, 1959–65, and named by the [[Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names]] for [[William Robert Blades]] who served as navigator during [[U.S. Navy Operation Highjump]] (1946–47) and [[Operation Deep Freeze]] (1955–59).
