'''David D. Balam''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[astronomer]] and a research associate with [[University of Victoria|University of Victoria's]] Department of [[Physics]] and [[Astronomy]], in [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], [[British Columbia]]. Specializing in the search for [[Near-Earth object]]s, Balam is one of the world's most prolific contributors to this research;<ref name="Star51098">{{cite news|title=B.C. telescope a key anti-asteroid sentry|last=Dickinson|first=Terence|date=May 10, 1998|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> only two astronomers have made more such discoveries than Balam.<ref name="VTC07" /> He is credited with the discovery or co-discovery of more than 600 asteroids, over a thousand extra-galactic [[supernovae]],<ref name="VTC07">{{cite web|url=http://www.canada.com/victoriatimescolonist/news/story.html?id=cfc22dca-2189-4f46-a624-5ad5e5784898&k=17971|title=t's a bird, it's a plane -- wait, no, it's UVic hurtling through the sky|date=June 1, 2007|publisher=canada.com/Victoria Times Colonist|accessdate=1 February 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604115852/http://www.canada.com/victoriatimescolonist/news/story.html?id=cfc22dca-2189-4f46-a624-5ad5e5784898&k=17971|archivedate=4 June 2011|df=}}</ref> and [[nova]]e in the [[galaxy M31]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2010}} Balam is also co-credited for the 1997 discovery of [[Comet Zhu-Balam]].<ref name="CBC98">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/1998/01/24/comet980124a.html|title=New comet named after astronomers|date=November 13, 1998|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=1 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ring.uvic.ca/98feb06/Balam.html|title=Sharp-eyed Balam co-discovers comet|last=McNeney|first=Mike|date=February 6, 1998|publisher=The Ring/University of Victoria|accessdate=1 February 2010}}</ref>

Among celestial bodies discovered by Balam are the asteroid [[150145 Uvic]], which he named for the University of Victoria,<ref name="VTC07" /> and [[197856 Tafelmusik]], named for the [[Tafelmusik Baroque Orchestra|Baroque orchestra]] in [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/music/story/2009/04/17/tafelmusik-asteroid.html|title=Asteroid has Tafelmusik's name on it|date=April 17, 2009|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=1 February 2010}}</ref> Currently, Balam conducts an optical transient survey (OTS) using the 1.82-m [[Plaskett Telescope]] of the [[National Research Council (Canada)|National Research Council]] of Canada.

The asteroid [[3749 Balam]] is named in his honour, recognizing the fact that he developed most of the software for the university's [[astrometric]] program on minor planets and comets.<ref>{{cite journal|date=May 31, 1988|title=Minor Planets and Comets|journal=Minor Planet Circular|publisher=[[International Astronomical Union]]|volume=13|issue=105|page=74|url=http://www.minorplanetcenter.org/iau/ECS/MPCArchive/1988/MPC_19880531.pdf|accessdate=February 1, 2010}}</ref>

